Whitehead, who won this year�۪s National Book Award for fiction, isn�۪t hurting for laurels���and yet it�۪s hard to imagine drafting a list of 2016�۪s mightiest books without including this phantasmagorical slash into the dark gut of American racism. Cora, an escaped slave, travels through the South on a literal subterranean train, each stop an object lesson in a different ghoulish facet of white supremacy. Her resolve and dignity are moving���but it�۪s the author�۪s playfulness and unpredictability that elevate this traditional tale of hardship into something singular, fugitive, and strange.

